<paragraph blockId="8.[140,1107,976,1073]" pageId="8" pageNumber="247">
Species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[251,341,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Haliplus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[251,341,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="247">Haliplus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Regimbart" authorityYear="1878" box="[394,494,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Haliplidae" genus="Peltodytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[394,494,976,1002]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="247">Peltodytes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are found in small ponds, lakes, and quiet streams where they are frequently observed crawling in algal mats or other vegetation. Adults eat insect eggs, algae, and polyps of Hydrozoa whereas larvae are algophilous (
<bibRefCitation author="Roughley RE" box="[885,1076,1046,1073]" pageId="8" pageNumber="247" pagination="138 - 143" refId="ref9663" refString="Roughley RE (2000 b) Haliplidae Aube, 1836. In: Arnett RH, Jr, Th omas MC (Eds) American Beetles, 1. Archeostemata, Myxophaga, Adephaga, Polyphaga: Staphyliniformia. Boca Raton, Florida: CRC Press, 138 - 143." type="book chapter" year="2000">Roughley 2000b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
